<div class='documentTop'><div>
  
  
    <h1>Office of the Prime Minister - Historical background</h1>
  
  </div></div>
  

  <div class="documentBody" id="Tekstinnhold">   
  <div>
    <p><strong>The Office of the Prime Minister has two principal functions: to serve as secretariat for the Council of State (the King, the prime minister and the eighteen government ministers) and to help the prime minister coordinate the government's work.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Under the same roof</strong><br />The prime minister has had a secretariat with more than one adviser since shortly after Prime Minister Johan Nygaardsvold and his government returned from exile in London in 1945.&nbsp; Soon this secretariat came to be known as the "Office of the Prime Minister".&nbsp; The Office was formally established with three state secretaries and a small number of civil servants in 1956.&nbsp; In 1969, the duties of the Council of State Secretariat were transferred to the Office of the Prime Minister, thus putting two important functions from the early 1800s – the secretariats of the Council of State and the prime minister – under the same roof.</p>
<p><strong>History</strong><br />After several centuries as an independent state, Norway became part of the kingdom of Denmark in 1536.&nbsp; With the defeat of Napoleon in 1814, Denmark, an ally of France, was compelled to sign the Treaty of Kiel, ceding Norway to the King of Sweden.&nbsp; However, the Norwegians were not willing to accept the Treaty and, electing Prince Christian Frederik of Denmark as king of Norway, they drew up their own constitution and appointed a Norwegian council of government.&nbsp; The first secretary of the council bore the title "Government Secretary" and took office in March 1814.&nbsp; In May 1814 Norway's first national assembly, convened at Eidsvoll, renamed the government council the "Council of State", while the secretary became the "State Secretary".&nbsp; The minister heading the government did not yet have a special title or a permanent secretary.</p>
<p><strong>Union with Sweden</strong><br />In November 1814, Norway was persuaded to accept the Treaty of Kiel and subsequently entered into a union with Sweden.&nbsp; King Christian Frederik stepped down and the king of Sweden was elected king of Norway as well.&nbsp; Although the Norwegian government continued to have its main seat in Christiania (the official name of the capital, Oslo, at the time), a special division of the government was established in Stockholm with its own secretariat.&nbsp; This division was known as the Council of State Division in Stockholm and consisted of the prime minister (the first being Peder Anker) and two ministers.&nbsp; When the King was in Stockholm, matters concerning Norway were decided by the King on the advice of the prime minister, who conveyed the views of the Norwegian government in Christiania.</p>
<p><strong>In the King's absence</strong><br />Council of State conferences in Christiania were chaired in the King's absence by the Swedish viceroy, the King's governor or the first minister.&nbsp; A secretary to support this office was needed, and this post was established in July 1829.&nbsp; In July 1873, the office of governor in Christiania was transformed into that of a prime minister, making first minister Frederik Stang the first prime minister in Christiania. This system, with a Norwegian prime minister both in Christiania and in Stockholm, was continued until the dissolution of the Swedish-Norewegian union in June 1905.&nbsp; In 1906, however, the position of secretary to the prime minister was abolished; in its place the prime minister used the officials of whichever ministry he headed to help him co-ordinate the government's work.&nbsp; The State Secretariat continued as a joint government office, administratively placed under the Ministry of Justice.&nbsp; In 1926 the State Secretariat changed its name to the Council of State Secretariat, and the state secretary's title was changed to Secretary to the Council of State.</p>
<p>In October 1939, it was decided that the prime minister would no longer be required to head a ministry, and the position of secretary to the prime minister was reintroduced.</p>
<p><br />&nbsp;</p>
